    <name>
      <text>Parabola (from FAC 3.2.1 Find k - line tangent to parabola, from graph)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p><b>(a)</b> Find the equation of the parabola shown in the diagram.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"></p>
<div style="margin-left:4em;margin-right:auto;">[[jsxgraph width='200px' height='200px']] JXG.Options.axis.ticks.majorHeight = 60; JXG.Options.axis.ticks.insertTicks = false; JXG.Options.axis.ticks.ticksDistance = 50; JXG.Options.text.fontSize = 16; var board = JXG.JSXGraph.initBoard(divid, {boundingbox:
    {#BB#}, axis: true, showCopyright: false, showNavigation:false}); var f = board.jc.snippet('{#quad#}', true, 'x', true); board.create('functiongraph', [f,-10,10],{strokeColor:'#003399',strokeWidth:2}); var xaxis = board.create('axis', [[0,0],[1,0]]);
    board.create('ticks', [xaxis, [{#A[1]#},{#B[1]#}]], {strokeColor: '#003399', majorHeight:15, drawLabels: true, label: { offset: [0, -10],anchorX: 'middle', anchorY: 'top' }}); var c = board.create('point',{#C#}, {name:'({#C[1]#},{#C[2]#})',size:2,fixed:true,strokeColor:'#003399',fillColor:'#003399',label:{anchorX:'right',anchorY:'top',offset:
    [0, -5]}}); [[/jsxgraph]]
</div>
<p></p>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \(y=\) [[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]

<p><b>(b) </b>The line with equation \(y= {@l@}\) is tangent to the parabola. Find the value of \(k.\)</p>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \(k=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p></p><p><b>(a)&nbsp;</b>The parabola has roots when \(x={@A[1]@}\) and \(x={@B[1]@}\) so its equation will be of the form \(y={@c*(x-A[1])*(x-B[1])@}\).</p><p>Since the parabola passes through&nbsp;\(({@C[1]@},{@C[2]@})\) we have \( {@C[2]@}={@c*ev((x-A[1])*(x-B[1]),x=C[1])@} \) thus \(c={@(C[2])/((C[1]-A[1])*(C[1]-B[1]))@}\).</p><p>So the parabola has equation \(y={@ta1@}\).</p><b>(b) </b>The line&nbsp;\(y= {@l@}\) is tangent to the parabola \( y = {@quad@} \) when these two intersect at one point.&nbsp;<p></p><p>So we solve \[ \begin{align*} {@quad@} &amp;= {@l@} \\ {@quad-l@} &amp;= 0 \end{align*}\]</p><p>To intersect at one point means that the&nbsp;discriminant of this quadratic equation should be \(0\).</p><p>We have \(a={@da@}\),&nbsp;\(b={@db@}\) and \(c={@dc@}\), so</p><p>\[ \begin{align*} b^2-4ac = ({@db@})^2 - 4({@da@})({@dc@}) &amp;= 0&nbsp; \\ {@expand((db)^2-4*da*dc)@} &amp;= 0&nbsp; \\ k &amp;= {@ta2@}\end{align*} \]</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
